    "active_paradigms": [
      {
        "idea": "Generalized Richards/asymmetric logistic with seed-dependent rate and monomer-dependent plateau",
        "description": "Replace the symmetric logistic with a Richards curve: y = c3 * x1^c6 / (1 + exp(-rate*(x0 - half_time)))^(1/c7), where c7 controls asymmetry of the sigmoid. Real amyloid aggregation curves are often right-skewed (slow approach to plateau). Also add monomer dependence to plateau via x1^c6 to capture concentration-dependent maximum aggregation. The exponent 1/c7 allows the curve to be asymmetric: c7>1 gives a curve that rises slowly then plateaus quickly, c7<1 gives the opposite. Keep half_time = c2 * x1^c4 / (1 + c5*x2) and rate = c0 * x1^c1 from the current best. This adds 2 constants (c6 for plateau scaling, c7 for shape asymmetry) for 8 total constants.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Validation NMSE on asymmetric sigmoidal datasets; hard cases where current logistic underfits the tail behavior",
        "cautions": "c7 must be kept positive to avoid complex numbers; initialize c7=1 (reduces to standard logistic), c6=0 (flat plateau). Use sp.exp carefully to avoid overflow. The expression (1 + exp(...))^(1/c7) needs c7 != 0; the least-squares fitter should handle this but initialize away from zero.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.symbolic_expression"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Double-sigmoidal / two-phase aggregation model capturing primary and secondary nucleation separately",
        "description": "Many amyloid systems show two-phase kinetics: a primary nucleation phase and a secondary nucleation (surface-catalyzed) phase. Model as sum of two logistic terms: y = c3/(1+exp(-c0*x1^c1*(x0-c2))) + c6/(1+exp(-c4*x1^c5*(x0-c7/(1+c8*x2)))). However this is 9 constants and may overfit. A simpler variant: use the Finke-Watzky inspired form y = c3 * x1^c4 * x0^c5 / (c6 + x0^c5) which is a Hill equation in time, capturing saturation. This is only 5 constants and naturally asymmetric. The Hill equation y = A*t^n/(K^n + t^n) is widely used for aggregation kinetics and gives a right-skewed sigmoidal that matches experimental data better than symmetric logistic.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Datasets where symmetric logistic fails; cross-protein evaluation datasets with unusual curve shapes",
        "cautions": "Hill equation in time requires t >= 0 which is satisfied since x0 is min-max normalized to [0,1]. Need c5 > 0 for proper shape. The monomer scaling x1^c4 on amplitude may interact with normalization. Initialize c5=2 (Hill coefficient), c6=0.5 (half-saturation at midpoint of normalized time).",
        "approach_type": "sympy.Hill_equation"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Knowles analytical solution structure: exponential approach with square-root seeding term",
        "description": "The Knowles 2009 Science paper gives an analytical solution for nucleation-elongation with secondary nucleation. The key structural insight is that the aggregation kinetics follow: M(t) = M_total * (1 - (cosh(kappa*t + phi) / cosh(phi))^(-2*k_plus*m_tot/kappa)) where kappa depends on sqrt(k2*k_plus)*m(t). A simplified but physically grounded approximation is: y = c3 / (1 + exp(-c0*(x1^c1 + c5*sqrt(x2)) * (x0 - c2/(x1^c4 + c6*sqrt(x2))))). This captures the sqrt(M0) dependence of the rate (from secondary nucleation theory) rather than linear M0 dependence. The sqrt(x2) term is more physically accurate than linear x2 for seeded aggregation. This keeps 7 constants with better physical grounding.",
        "what_to_optimize": "Seeded aggregation datasets where seed concentration scaling matters; cross-protein evaluation with varied seed concentrations",
        "cautions": "sqrt(x2) requires x2 >= 0 which is physically guaranteed (seed concentration). sp.sqrt is available. The combined rate term (x1^c1 + c5*sqrt(x2)) must remain positive; initialize c5 positive. This may fit better on seeded datasets but similar to current on unseeded ones.",
        "approach_type": "sympy.sqrt_seeding"
      }
    ],
